What is an Array?
An array is a collection of multiple values of the same data type stored in continuous memory 
locations under a single variable name.

Example:
int a[] = {10, 20, 30};

What can an Array do?

âœ” Store multiple values
âœ” Access elements using index
âœ” Fast data access
âœ” Simple and efficient

ğŸ”´ Limitations of Array
Even though arrays are useful, they have some limitations:

1ï¸ Fixed Size
Array size must be decided at the time of creation
Size cannot be changed at runtime
int a[] = new int[5];   // size fixed

2ï¸ Memory Wastage
If the array size is large but usage is small â†’ memory wasted
If array size is small â†’ cannot add more elements

3ï¸ No Built-in Methods
Arrays do not provide methods like add, remove, search
Manual coding is required for operations

4ï¸ Cannot Shrink or Grow
Once created, array size cannot increase or decrease

What is an ArrayList?
An ArrayList is a resizable array that can grow or shrink at runtime.

Array vs ArrayList:
An array is a fixed-size data structure, whereas an ArrayList is a dynamic data structure that can grow or shrink at runtime.

Example:
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

Key Features of ArrayList

âœ” Dynamic resizing
âœ” Stores objects (uses wrapper classes)
âœ” Easy element manipulation
âœ” Part of Collections Framework
